To debug cases like this, it would be good to include the exact `./gradlew sonarqube ...` command you executed, and its output when using the `--info` flag.

For now, I can say that you should not have to specify the jacoco report path explicitly, the sonarqube gradle plugin should be able to find it. Make sure the jacoco plugin is activated, for example by having a line like this:

    apply plugin: &#39;jacoco&#39;

As far as I know the following properties are unnecessary to specify, the plugin detects them automatically:

&gt;     property &quot;sonar.java.source&quot;, &quot;1.8&quot;
&gt;     property &quot;sonar.java.binaries&quot;, &quot;build/libs/xyz-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.jar&quot;
&gt;     property &quot;sonar.java.coveragePlugin&quot;, &quot;jacoco&quot;
&gt;     property &quot;sonar.tests&quot;, &quot;src/test&quot;
&gt;     property &quot;sonar.java.test.binaries&quot;, &quot;build/classes/java/test&quot;

Lastly, as the [documentation][1] explains, the best place to configure `sonar.login` is not in `build.gradle`, but in a `gradle.properties` file, as `systemProp.sonar.login=&lt;token&gt;`.


  [1]: https://docs.sonarqube.org/latest/analysis/scan/sonarscanner-for-gradle/

